";}i:6;a:12:{s:5:"title";s:28:"Integrating JDBC with ArcSDE";s:4:"link";s:69:"http://www.jdoneill.com/blog/2005/03/13/integrating-jdbc-with-arcsde/";s:8:"comments";s:78:"http://www.jdoneill.com/blog/2005/03/13/integrating-jdbc-with-arcsde/#comments";s:7:"pubdate";s:31:"Sun, 13 Mar 2005 15:24:22 +0000";s:2:"dc";a:1:{s:7:"creator";s:3:"dop";}s:8:"category";s:23:"ArcGIS ServerJavaArcSDE";s:4:"guid";s:69:"http://www.jdoneill.com/blog/2005/03/13/integrating-jdbc-with-arcsde/";s:11:"description";s:325:"JDBC is an efficient means to connect to a wide range of SQL Databases and access the data within.  ESRI's ArcSDE is a value added database application server on top of relational databases which is efficient in spatially enabling databases and accessing the spatial content in the database.  Combining the use of these [...]";s:7:"content";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";s:5427:"	<p>JDBC is an efficient means to connect to a wide range of SQL Databases and access the data within.  ESRI&#8217;s ArcSDE is a value added database application server on top of relational databases which is efficient in spatially enabling databases and accessing the spatial content in the database.  Combining the use of these two technologies to analyze your spatial data can provide an efficient development model for your spatial applications. </p>
	<p>The example we will look at here today is a web application which queries a spatially enabled database for place names.  The selected place name will be mapped on the web canvas.  The web application model will be a front servlet controller model as specified by the Core J2EE Pattern Catalog.  The presentation tier request mechanism must control and coordinate processing of each user across  multiple requests.  This example will use a servlet which serves as a single entry point for all requests.  An input form collects all the initial input parameters from the user.  By submitting this input form, the controller places the input parameter values in the session so they can be accessed by several pages.  Views are created to display the dynamic content provided by the View Beans.  A master view displays the entire set of a SQL query and a details view displays individual query records.  The View Beans are Java Bean wrappers which do the work or retrieving and displaying SQL and Spatial data.  View Beans allow for more control over how data is displayed when rendered by web pages.  A relational database is accessed transparently in this model by a custom Java Bean to access data through JDBC and ArcObjects.  When we access the SHAPE column of a spatially enabled table through JDBC we use it as a Java Object as follows: </p>
	<p><code>Object ret = getDBSelect().getColumn( SHAPE_LABEL );</code></p>
	<p>Where <code>SHAPE_LABEL</code> represents the name of the spatial column.  This value may vary depending on which database you are using with ArcSDE.  We can convert the object to string to get a long binary translation of our SHAPE column: </p>
	<p><code>massageOutput(ret)</code></p>
	<p><code><br />
   /*************************************************************<br />
   * Formats code so that is HTML Friendly<br />
   * @param in The incoming String<br />
   * @return The formatted String<br />
   */<br />
   protected String massageOutput(Object in) {<br />
      Object out = in;<br />
      //Place code here to format your output<br />
      return (out != null) ? out.toString() : "";<br />
   }<br />
</code></p>
	<p>In order to map our selected query we need to make sense of the SHAPE output.  We can use the Java API to ArcObjects to accomplish this.  We will use the Java API in a local context which allows our J2EE application server to manage the contexts of the spatial objects we create.  ESRI is currently not supporting this approach, but it is a legal use of ArcObjects.  I will have to submit another web log on the tips and tricks for this approach.  We can use the server, database, user and password parameters from our JDBC connection.  We only need to add the service port, default is 5151.  Once we make a connection we can begin using ArcObjects to access the same data, create a feature class from the result, and ultimately return a geometry type for the SHAPE column.  </p>
	<p><code><br />
// --- a query definition represents a database query on a table or feature class<br />
IQueryDef queryDef = wksp.createQueryDef();<br />
queryDef.setTables( SDE_TABLE );<br />
queryDef.setSubFields( SHAPE_LABEL );<br />
queryDef.setWhereClause( OBJECTID_LABEL + " = " + OBJECTID );<br />
// --- the openFeatureQuery method on a workspace can be used to create<br />
// --- a feature class based on a query definition<br />
IFeatureClassContainer fcContainer = new IFeatureClassContainerProxy(<br />
wksp.openFeatureQuery( "SHAPE Query", queryDef ) );<br />
IFeatureClass fc = null;<br />
if( fcContainer.getClassCount() != 1 ){<br />
System.err.println( "Failed to create feature class by query" );<br />
}else{<br />
// --- get the feature class<br />
fc = fcContainer.esri_getClass( 0 );<br />
// --- the actual geometry type is defined by the esriGeometryType enumeration<br />
int geometryType = fc.getFeatureType();<br />
// --- the type of feature in this feature class<br />
switch(geometryType){<br />
case esriGeometryType.esriGeometryPoint: type = "Point";  break;<br />
case esriGeometryType.esriGeometryMultipoint: type = "MultiPoint"; break;<br />
case esriGeometryType.esriGeometryPolyline: type = "Polyline"; break;<br />
case esriGeometryType.esriGeometryPolygon: type = "Polygon"; break;<br />
</code></p>
	<p>Where <code>SDE_TABLE</code> represents the name of the spatial table and <code>OBJECTID_LABEL</code> represents the name of the OBJECTID column.  We use a <code>QueryDef</code> object representing a database query on our table.  The <code>openFeatureQuery</code> method on the <code>IFeatureWorkspace</code> interface can be used to create a <code>FeatureClass</code> based on our <code>QueryDef</code>.  We can QueryInterface, or Proxy, from the return <code>IFeatureDataset</code> to an <code>IFeatureClassContainer</code> interface to provide us access to feature classes.  Once we have the feature class, we can determine it&#8217;s geometry type and return that to the user.  </p>
