";}i:7;a:12:{s:5:"title";s:38:"ArcGIS Server distributed architecture";s:4:"link";s:54:"http://www.jdoneill.com/blog/2005/03/10/arcgis-server/";s:8:"comments";s:63:"http://www.jdoneill.com/blog/2005/03/10/arcgis-server/#comments";s:7:"pubdate";s:31:"Thu, 10 Mar 2005 20:06:22 +0000";s:2:"dc";a:1:{s:7:"creator";s:3:"dop";}s:8:"category";s:27:"ArcGIS ServerJavaArcObjects";s:4:"guid";s:54:"http://www.jdoneill.com/blog/2005/03/10/arcgis-server/";s:11:"description";s:409:"ESRI’s ArcGIS Server provides a platform development environment for a subset of ArcObjects technology.  As a value added product, ArcGIS Server components include a Server Object Container (SOC), Server Object Manager (SOM), and an Application Developer Framework (ADF).

Server Object Manager (SOM)
The Server Object Manager component of ArcGIS Server manages deployment of ArcObjects Containers for [...]";s:7:"content";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";s:3753:"	<p>ESRI’s ArcGIS Server provides a platform development environment for a subset of ArcObjects technology.  As a value added product, ArcGIS Server components include a Server Object Container (SOC), Server Object Manager (SOM), and an Application Developer Framework (ADF).</p>
	<p><em>Server Object Manager (SOM)</em><br />
The Server Object Manager component of ArcGIS Server manages deployment of ArcObjects Containers for the purpose of managing the lifecycle of the objects.  SOM administrators create SOC instances based on service configurations deployed on container machines which support ArcObjects.  This provides a scalable platform for the execution of remote multi-user ArcObjects applications.  </p>
	<p><em>Server Object Containers (SOC)</em><br />
The Server Object Containers are multi-threaded executables configured to support one to four concurrent instances determined by the isolation levels.  High isolation deployments support one instance per SOC executable, low isolation deployments support up to four instances per SOC executable.  </p>
	<p><em>ArcGIS Server Platform Configurations</em><br />
ArcGIS server can be architected into multiple tier configurations.  Single-tier configurations provide all ArcGIS Server components on one platform or hardware machine.  Such configurations can be on multiple platforms to allow for network load balancing.  This configuration is appropriate for development and prototyping or production sites with a limited number of service requests.  A two-tier ArcGIS Server configuration separates the ArcGIS Server components from the data components.  This allows a single copy of the data to support multiple ArcGIS containers.  This configuration is most appropriate for development and prototyping or small production sites.  The three-tiered configuration is the most appropriate production configuration as it separates ArcGIS Server components among two tiers and data.  Couple this into a high availability configuration, or server farm, allows for the highest failover rates and is most appropriate for large production sites.  </p>
	<p>Integrating the ArcGIS Sever platform into a distributed n-tier enterprise system has many challenges.  The main challenge is recognizing the components ArcGIS server provides and where they fit into a distributed n-tier enterprise system.  One way J2EE business tier components can communicate through the integration-tier into a proposed GIS EIS system is with the Java Connector Architecture (JCA).  The JCA proves Java&#8217;s flexibility by integrating  non-java data sources and/or applications.  The business flow to integrate ArcGIS server is as follows: </p>
	<p>1: The Connection Factory interface provides a connection to an EIS instance.<br />
2: A transaction manager coordinates transactions across multiple resource managers.<br />
3: Resource Adapter provides an API through which an application can access a resource outside of J2EE and support for local transactions performed on the underlying EIS.<br />
4: The ESRI Java runtime is our EIS in this architecture.  This is intended to isolate all threading and server socket connections used by the ESRI Java runtime.<br />
5: ArcObjects COM represents the system level EIS.  The ESRI Java runtime is responsible for making connections into the system level EIS.  </p>
	<p>All of these tiers will work together by sharing components and communicating in ways native to each module.  </p>
	<p>A more modern approach at realizing a n-tier enterprise architecture would be a Service Oriented Architecture (SOA).  More generically, an internal web service described could be represented as an Enterprise Service Bus (ESB) with web services as one type of service choice.
</p>
